  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws are primarily established through international organizations and agreements, and they set the standards for anti-money laundering (AML) practices that countries are expected to adopt and enforce. Here are some key components of international AML laws:\n\n### 1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\nThe FATF is the primary global body that sets standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Established in 1989, the FATF has issued **FATF Recommendations**, which are widely recognized as the international standard for AML and Counter-Terrorist Financing (CTF).\n\n### 2. **United Nations Conventions**\nSeveral UN conventions address money laundering:\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Known as the Vienna Convention, it was the first international treaty to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention requires states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to prevent it.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\nThe EU has implemented several AML directives that member states must transpose into national law:\n   - **First EU AML Directive (1991)**\n   - **Second EU AML Directive (2001)**\n   - **Third EU AML Directive (2005)**\n   - **Fourth EU AML Directive (2015, amended in 2018)**  \n   - **Fifth EU AML Directive (2018)**  \n   - **Sixth EU AML Directive (2023)**  \nThese directives progressively strengthen AML measures, including enhanced due diligence, beneficial ownership transparency, and stricter penalties for non-compliance.\n\n### 4. **Basel Principles**\nThe Basel Committee on Banking Supervision issued the **Basel Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision**, which includes guidelines on managing money laundering risks in the banking sector.\n\n### 5. **Regional AML Bodies**\nIn addition to the FATF, regional AML bodies have been established to implement AML standards in specific regions:\n   - The **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)**  \n   - The **Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF)**  \n   - The **Middle East and North Africa Financial Action Task Force (MENAFATF)**  \n   - The **Eastern and Southern Africa Anti-Money Laundering Group (ESAAMLG)**  \n\n### 6. **Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)**\nMany countries have MLATs in place to facilitate cross-border cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases.\n\n### Enforcement and Compliance\nCountries are expected to implement these international standards through national legislation. The FATF conducts regular evaluations of member countries to assess their compliance with AML standards. Non-compliant countries may be placed on the FATF's **\"gray list\"** or **\"blacklist\"**, which can result in financial and reputational consequences.\n\nIn summary, international laws against money laundering are robust and continually evolving to address emerging threats. Countries are required to adopt these standards and enforce them through their legal systems.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
